   <indicator ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output Indicator</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Extent of country wide audit coverage</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2013">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">35% annual operational plans</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will continue to support enhanced the audit capacity of the OAG through strengthening the audit tools, fundamental changing environment of audit concepts and principles and upgrading the skills and knowledge of auditors migrated to technology driven accounting procedures and equip them with technological tools
9 ACCA qualified,</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Annual operational plan was approved in January 2021. Based on the activities identified in the annual operational plan, the OAG has been conducting its business under close supervision by the Monitoring and evaluation sub-committee of the SAI Team. The following are the performance result of the annual operational plan in 2021
&#x2022;	In order to secure its independence through Audit Act in accordance to the requirement of Lima declaration, the OAG revisited and updated the draft Audit Legislation. The Draft Audit Legislation describes all the pre-requisites for independent Supreme Audit Institution (SAI) in accordance to INTOSAI-P 10. The Draft Audit Legislation was submitted to the concerned authorities for approval. Approval of the Draft Audit Legislation is beyond the scope of the OAG. However, the OAG should prepare all the necessary preconditions for enhancing its independence. 
&#x2022;	The design of a Management Information System that facilitates the flow of information among the OAG organs was planned to be implemented. The system was completed in the 3rd quarter of 2021 and took two more months for testing and acceptance. The system is approved by all users and will be used starting January 2022. The system currently hosts the two Audit Departments, the Finance and Administration, the HRD and the IT Divisions, as well as Library, Stores, and the secretary of the Auditor General. 
&#x2022;	The OAG completed the updated the Job description in 2020 to respond to the structural and operational change made during the past three decades. In 2021, the job description for store keeper, communication officer, and Network Administrator were added. 
&#x2022;	The development of a strategic plan for the Administration and Finance Division that cover three years was completed. However, its approval is awaiting the implementation matrix which detail the activities to be carried during the three years. 

&#x2022;	The OAG website &#x201C;oageritrea.org&#x201D; that was launched in 2020 was in need of upgrading. Accordingly, all necessary updates and debugs was made to the website leading to improved efficiency.

&#x2022;	The Performance Audit (PA) Unit which was established in 2018 was reinforced by equipping the staff with training and tools. 
&#x2022;	The management pulled resources from the two Audit Departments to establish a Quality Assurance Review Unit. The members of the team are Financial Auditors with no experience in quality assurance review..In addressing this challenge, the OAG prepared a template and guideline for the preparation of &#x201C;Annual Audit Reports&#x201D; in 2020. In 2021 a reporting template for Corporate Services was prepared and implemented.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The support enhanced the audit capacity of the OAG through strengthening the audit tools, fundamental changing environment of audit concepts and principles and upgrading the skills and knowledge of auditors migrated to technology driven accounting procedures and equip them with technological tools</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">To secure its independence through Audit Act in accordance to the requirement of Lima declaration, with the support of UNDP the Office of the Auditor General (OAG) drafted an Audit Legislation and was submitted to the concerned authorities for approval. With the installation of solar power the power supply in the OAG has improved significantly. An assessment of the financial impact of the solar power found out that there was a 57% cost saving on electric consumption. Th OAG also developed Integrated Reporting template that can be used by Supreme Audit Institutions(SAI) ,guideline on the process and stages of planning , standard planning guideline that can consistently be implemented across all its organs , system for monitoring and evaluating the strategic and operational plans, delegation policy on delegation of authority, new organizational structure and job descriptions. In addition the Code of Ethics was revised to comply with the International Standard for Supreme Audit Institutions, staff development and training policy was designed, and stakeholder engagement strategy drafted. Comparing with past years performance, the coverage has improved significantly. The time an audit takes to be completed has reduced by a minimum of 30-40% resulting to an increase in coverage by more than 100%. This improvement was as a result of the intensive trainings conducted and the intrudction of policy in 2019 for a strict control on audit budget time [Office of the Auditor General Annual Report].</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Upgrading the skills and knowledge of auditors migrated to technology driven accounting procedures and equip them with technological tools</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">UNDP supported training of 151 staff of various government offices in Compliance Audit, IT Auditing and Internal Auditing; 55 people in Financial Audit and Compliance Audit (16 female); and 60 staff (40% women) in Auditing, Accounting and IT. With the training support of UNDP, OAG was able to meet ~50% of its staff requirement (E.g. Number of auditors increased from 40 in 2016 to 80 in 2020, and all current B.A. degree holders staff are currently attending ACCA courses). This has improved the image of OAG and enhanced job satisfaction. The OAG has made good progress in gender equality as women currently constitute 31.5% of the staff in the departments and sections</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
